The Baltimore Orioles and Manny Machados Performance

One of my course objectives was to connect with my son, Anthony, on Sports. To help achieve this, I decided for my project to use the baseball metrics I learned about during the course to analyze my son’s favorite baseball team, the Baltimore Orioles, and his favorite baseball player, Manny Machado.

Anthony was a Baltimore Orioles fan from about 2011 until 2018 when Manny Machado left the team. We took a mother/son trip to Baltimore in 2013. Anthony was 10. We attended the June 26, 2013 game against the Cleveland Indians where they won 7-3 and the June 27, 2013 game against the New York Yankees where they won 4-3. With 40,000 fans in attendance at Camden Yards, it is a memory we will never forget.

Each night, we arrived to the game two hours early and after the game, we would hurry to the player parking exit trying to see of one of the players might stop for an autograph on the way out. You know you have a BIG FAN when at 10 years old your son wants to spend 7 hours at the field for any chance of seeing his favorite player.

I never really understood why the Orioles became his favorite team. I assumed they must be a winning team. We are not from Maryland and Manny wasn’t playing for the team when he became a fan in 2011 (at age 8). Manny did join the team in 2012 and even though the Orioles had some tough years, Manny seemed to be the reason Anthony continued to root for them.

For the team review: I will look at the Baltimore Orioles Win Percent (Wpct) and how that compared to the Pythagorean Expectation predicted win percentage (ExpWpct) from 2009 to 2019.

For the player review: I will look at the value Manny Machado added to the Orioles while playing for them from 2012 to 2018 by comparing Manny’s value (Runs Created and WAR) to the value other known 3rd basemen had. I will focus on player statics from their 1st, 3rd, 5th and 8th seasons.

Baltimore Oriole’s Team Review - Win Percent (Wpct) and how that Compared to Pythagorean Expectation Predicted Win Percentage (ExpWpct)

First I will create the Wpct variable to see what the Orioles actual win percentage for each season between 2009 and 2020 was. Win percent is the percentage of total games played that the team won and is calculated as wins divided by wins plus losses (W/(W+L)).

Then I will create the ExpWpct variable that calculates the Pythagorean Expectation predicted win percentage. The Pythagorean Expectations formula is runs to the second power divided by runs to the second power plus runs allowed to the second power (R2/(R2+RA2)) and is essentially the percentage of games a team “should” or is “expected” to win.

teams = teams %>% mutate(Wpct = W/(W+L)) %>% mutate(ExpWpct = (R^2)/(R^2 + RA^2))

In reviewing the plot of Wpct versus ExpWpct the “expected win percent” appears to be a strong predictor of actual “win percent”. There is a moderate to strong positive relationship although you can see from table that ExpWpct was less than Wpct for 6 out of 10 years and the biggest gap between ExpWpct and Wpct was in 2012 when they were expected to win about 50% of games and they ended up winning about 57%.

## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

The Orioles best season from 2009 to 2019 was 2014. They had almost a 59% win percent that year. There win percent lept from 43% in 2011 to 57% in 2012, the year Manny Machado joined the team. It remained between 50% and 59% over the next five years (2012 to 2016). They had some great years, outperforming projections year over year, but in 2018 they took a significant drop in wins.

Could this have had anything to with them trading Manny Machado to the Dodgers in 2018 (ended up with the San Diego Padres)? The Orioles entered the 2018 season with signs of being playoff contenders, but after trading Zach Britton to the Yankees, Jonathan Schoop to the Brewers, Brad Brach, Darren O’Day and Kevin Gausman to the Braves; Manny’s leaving seemed to be the last straw and they ended 2018 with only a 29% Wpct.

Will they turn things around? 2019 seemed to be a little better than 2018.

Manny Machado Peer Comparison - A Comparison of Runs Created and WAR to other Known 3rd Base Players.

So did Manny really make Anthony a fan?

If I compare Manny’s performance to other 3rd Base Players, does he really stand out? I decided to check it out. The players I included are:

  • Ryan Zimmerman ~ Washington Nationals
  • Rafael Devers ~ Boston Red Sox
  • Nolan Arenado ~ Colorado Rockies
  • Nicholas Castellanos ~ Detroit Tigers
  • Manny Machado ~ Baltimore Orioles
  • Kyle Seager ~ Seattle Mariners
  • Kris Bryant ~ Chicago Cubs
  • Anthony Rendon ~ Washington Nationals

I pulled the stats for each of these players from their 1st, 3rd, 5th and 8th Seasons playing.

Note: Rafael Devers and Kris Bryant haven’t played an 8th Season yet. The low average run figure for Season 8 is because Season 8 was in 2020 for three of the players (Nolan Arenado, Nicholas Castellanos and Anthony Rendon) and the 2020 Season was cut short due to COVID.

First I will compare the number of Runs each player had. The average number of runs (R) for all the players in all the seasons of our data set is about 62. Season 1 average is 33, Season 2 average is 80, Season 3 average is 95 and Season 8 average is 41.

Next I will look at Runs Created. Runs created (RC) is calculated as hits plus walks times total bases divided by at bats plus walks ((H+BB)*TB)/(AB+BB)).

Runs created is an indicator of how many runs have resulted from a player. Not only the runs they made, but the runs they created from hitting singles, doubles, triples, home runs, etc.

Players = Players %>% mutate(RC = ((H+BB)*TB)/(AB+BB))

Next I will create a simple linear regression model using runs created to predict runs. Runs = slope times Runs Created plus intercept (R = (0.893)(RC)+(-0.061)). With a p value of <2e-16 *** being less than 0.05, we can say that RC is a significant predictor of R.

Recall that R-squared ranges from 0 to 1. A value of 1 would indicate a “perfect” model that explains all of the variance in the response (y) variable. A value of 0 would be an extremely poor model. With an R-squared of 0.95, we can determine this is a good model.

LinearRegressM = lm(R ~ RC, playerstable)

In reviewing the Runs Created metric, I would say Ryan Zimmerman and Nolan Arenado add most value.

Now let’s compare WAR for these players. WAR is used to decide how many more wins one player is worth over another who plays in the same position. More specifically, Wins Above Replacement (WAR) is a baseball statistic used to measure a player’s total contribution to the team. When a team is contemplating trading one player for another, WAR is a measure reviewed to see what increased value the trade may provide to the team.

In reviewing WAR Ratings on stathead.com from the 1st, 3rd, 5th and 8th seasons, I found Manny Machado helped the Orioles win more games than could have been expected by a replacement level player.

Season 1: Manny’s WAR was 1.6, average WAR for all players was 1.5

Season 3: Manny’s WAR was 2.2, average WAR for all players was 3.7

Season 5: Manny’s WAR was 7.3, average wAR for all players was 5.3

Season 8: Manny’s WAR was 2.6, average WAR for all players was 1.3

WAR Performance Guide:

Scrub: 0-1 WAR, Role Player: 1-2 WAR, Solid Starter: 2-3 WAR, Good Player: 3-4 WAR, All-Star: 4-5 WAR, Superstar: 5-6 WAR, MVP: 6+ WAR

mean(playerstable$WAR)

Manny’s WAR was below average in Seasons 1 and 3. Players in their 1st Season tend to play at Scrub or Role Player levels, but Kris Bryant stood out as a Superstar. In their 3rd Season they move to Good Player or All Star levels. By the 5th Season they move to Superstar and MVP levels. Manny’s WAR of 7.3 (same as Ryan Zimmerman’s) in Season 5 was MVP level according to the WAR Performance Guide.

I wonder what would have happened if the Orioles picked up Ryan Zimmerman when they traded Manny. Ryan Zimmerman clearly stands out even among the best 3B Players, followed by Nolan Arenado. Manny Machado and Kris Bryant are a close 3rd in terms of performance and value add for the team.
